STRUCTURAL ALTERATIONS. Along with functional disorders, CMD may also be a consequence of structural alterations, particularly in patients with risk factors for CAD or with underlying cardiomyopathies. Structural abnormalities associated with CMD are mainly represented by luminal narrowing of the intramural arterioles and capillaries, perivascular Ô¨Åbrosis, and capillary rarefaction, often in the context of increased left ventricular mass (2). These phenomena are consistently documented in patients with hypertrophic cardiomyopathy (HCM) and hypertensive heart disease (13). In both of these conditions, the morphological changes observed are characterized by adverse remodeling of arterioles, resulting in medial wall thickening (mainly because of smooth muscle hypertrophy and increased collagen deposition) and variable degrees of intimal thickening, causing altered coronary physiology and CBF (13). An important common feature to these conditions is the diffuse nature of ‚Äúmicrovascular remodeling,‚Äù which extends to the whole left ventricle.

ASSESSMENT OF CMD
Invasive and noninvasive techniques assessing the function and integrity of coronary microvasculature are required to evaluate the presence of CMD (Tables 1 and 2).
NONINVASIVE TECHNIQUES. Different noninvasive modalities can be used to characterize CMD. Notably, using noninvasive techniques, the diagnosis of CMD should be made only after the exclusion of obstructive CAD using computed tomography coronary angiography or invasive coronary angiography. Additionally, noninvasive techniques do not directly assess the inclination of coronary arteries to spasm, but do only test the vasodilator capacity of VSMC, allowing the identiÔ¨Åcation of impaired vasodilatory capacity of the microcirculation.
Transthoracic Doppler echocardiography allows measurement of the maximal diastolic Ô¨Çow in the epicardial arteries during rest and adenosine/dipyridamole/regadenoson stress, known as coronary Ô¨Çow velocity ratio (CFVR) (14). It is often limited to the left anterior descending artery region, implicitly

