CENTRAL ILLUSTRATION Role of Coronary Microvascular Dysfunction Across Different Cardiovascular Diseases

Del Buono, M.G. et al. J Am Coll Cardiol. 2021;78(13):1352‚Äì1371.
CMD plays a major role in determining myocardial ischemia in many cardiovascular conditions, including angina with and without obstructive coronary artery disease, myocardial infarction, nonischemic cardiomyopathies, takotsubo syndrome, and heart failure (especially HF with preserved ejection fraction). Many molecular, functional, and structural mechanisms may be involved and are related to the underlying disease. ACS ¬º acute coronary syndrome; CABG ¬º coronary artery bypass graft; CAD ¬º coronary artery disease; CMD ¬º coronary microvascular dysfunction; HF ¬º heart failure; HFpEF ¬º HF with preserved ejection fraction; INOCA ¬º ischemia with nonobstructive coronary arteries; MINOCA ¬º myocardial infarction with nonobstructive coronary arteries; PCI ¬º percutaneous coronary intervention.

study suggested that there is a worse prognosis in patients with INOCA, and low CFR was a robust independent predictor of MACE (28). These Ô¨Åndings were then extended, and a reduced CFR (CFR <2) was found as a powerful incremental predictor of MACE in both women and men (29). Moreover, along with an adverse cardiovascular prognosis, INOCA patients have also a poor physical functioning and a reduced

quality of life (30). Recently, the CorMicA (CORonary MICrovascular Angina) trial provided proof-ofconcept clinical evidence that a strategy of adjunctive invasive testing for disorders of coronary function linked with stratiÔ¨Åed medical therapy led to improvements in patient outcomes, including reduction in angina severity and better quality of life (31).

