Sarcoidosis is a multisystem noncaseating granulomatous disease. Up to 25% of patients with sarcoidosis have myocardial involvement, although only 5% of patients show clinical manifestations of cardiac disease; angina is a frequent symptom in sarcoidosis, whereas only a limited fraction of patients have obstructive CAD. Many studies, using noninvasive methods, demonstrated reduced CFR in patients with sarcoidosis; however, the underlying putative mechanisms are not well understood (83). CMD in patients with H CM . The hallmark of HCM is the massive hypertrophy, which is generally asymmetric and develops independently of hemodynamic or systemic triggers. Along with cardiomyocyte hypertrophy, HCM phenotype involves a complex interplay of myocyte disarray, interstitial Ô¨Åbrosis with thickened Ô¨Åbers encasing myocytes, mitral valve and subvalvular abnormalities, and coronary microvascular remodeling. These structural abnormalities are considered the most relevant substrate of CMD that, in the presence of increased oxygen demand, ultimately exposes to recurrent myocardial ischemia and its sequelae (13). Several studies have shown that

CFR is more blunted in the subendocardium and the more hypertrophied areas, but is also impaired in the nonhypertrophied ones, in line with the evidence of a widespread remodeling of intramural arterioles at autopsy (84-86). CMD over time may also lead to recurrent ischemia and myocyte death leading to foci of replacement Ô¨Åbrosis, as shown by the presence of areas of late gadolinium enhancement at CMR. Furthermore, CMD assessed by PET has been shown to be a long-term predictor of adverse remodeling, systolic dysfunction, clinical deterioration, and death in HCM (84-86). CMD in patients with dilated cardiomyopathy. Previous studies have identiÔ¨Åed myocardial perfusion abnormalities in patients with dilated cardiomyopathy with moderate or severe adverse remodeling. Myocardial ischemia attributable to CMD is an independent contributor in the progression of the disease (87,88). However, further work is required to elucidate the temporal relationship between perfusion abnormalities and ventricular dysfunction in dilated cardiomyopathy. The degree of CMD has been shown to be an independent predictor of CVD events and is

JACC VOL. 78, NO. 13, 2021 SEPTEMBER 28, 2021:1352‚Äì1371

Del Buono et al Coronary Microvascular Dysfunction in Cardiovascular Diseases

1365

associated with increased risk of death and further progression of HF (87).
IATROGENIC CMD
Iatrogenic CMD may occur after percutaneous or surgical coronary revascularization, limiting their clinical beneÔ¨Åt. In patients undergoing PCI, the mechanisms underlying CMD are distal embolization of plaque material during the stenting procedure or functional alterations, which may overlap a preexistent CMD. Ischemia caused by balloon inÔ¨Çations and the stretch of the artery may in fact elicit a reÔ¨Çex
sympathetic increase of a-adrenergic constrictor tone
in the microcirculation (89). This complication often results in troponin elevation, which occurs in onethird of patients and is associated with an increased risk of subsequent major CVD events, death, myocardial infarction, and re-PCI. In patients with stable CAD undergoing elective PCI, IMR (IMR $25) measured immediately after PCI predicts adverse events independently of fractional Ô¨Çow reserve, indicating the prognostic importance of CMD despite successful epicardial coronary revascularization (90). In patients undergoing CABG, a number of factors can inÔ¨Çuence microvascular function, including cardioplegia, extracorporeal circulation, periprocedural ischemia, and inÔ¨Çammatory response. Similarly, the prognostic impact of myocardial damage following CABG is as clinically relevant as the one following PCI, suggesting that patient prognosis is eventually driven by the extent of necrosis regardless of the mechanisms responsible for its occurrence (91). A potential explanation is that myocardial damage might lead to increased mortality as a result of electrical instability or of persistent myocardial ischemia associated with CMD.
Furthermore, CMD is also common in heart transplant recipients with cardiac allograft vasculopathy (CAV). Of importance, CMD has been shown to be independently associated with the onset of epicardial CAV and associated with a higher risk of death, regardless of CAV onset (92).
TARGETING CMD
To date, there are no speciÔ¨Åc therapeutic strategies targeting CMD validated by large-scale randomized clinical trials, and therefore, treatment of patients with CMD should be targeted on the risk factors and speciÔ¨Åc phenotypic presentation.
Physical training, smoking cessation, and intentional weight loss (in obese patients) have consistently been shown to be beneÔ¨Åcial in improving CFR,

exercise capacity, cardiorespiratory Ô¨Åtness, and CVD outcomes (93-96) (Table 3).
In patients with high levels of low-density lipoprotein cholesterol or at high CVD risk proÔ¨Åle, statin therapy exerts signiÔ¨Åcant off-target effects as a consequence of its anti-inÔ¨Çammatory and antioxidant properties, and previous studies have conÔ¨Årmed its efÔ¨Åcacy in improving CFR (97).
Third-generation beta-blockers, such as nebivolol and carvedilol, and dihydropyridine-type calciumchannel blockers have been shown to modify endothelial function along with their effect on reducing myocardial oxygen demand and increasing diastolic perfusion time (98,99). Beta-blockers are the cornerstone of therapy in HFrEF patients; they have also been shown to improve angina symptoms in MVA patients with effort-induced angina and evidence of increased adrenergic activity, and are considered as Ô¨Årst-line therapy in this patient population (98,99). However, currently there is no evidence of beneÔ¨Åt for beta-blocker use in patients with HFpEF (100). Nondihydropyridine calcium-channel blockers are effective in patients with MVA often triggered by microvascular spasm, as well as in patients with documented epicardial coronary spasm (101).
The large TREND (Trial on Reversing ENdothelial Dysfunction) (102) provided evidence that angiotensin-converting enzyme inhibitors, in particular quinapril, was able to reverse endothelial dysfunction, and these beneÔ¨Åcial effects have been replicated by several other studies involving angiotensin II receptor blockers. Angiotensin-converting enzyme inhibitors and angiotensin II receptor blockers are the Ô¨Årst-line therapy in patients with HFrEF (99) but failed to improve overall morbidity or mortality in patients with HFpEF (100). In patients with INOCA, enalapril improved CFR as well as exercise parameters in patients with MVA in a cohort of 20 Taiwanese patients compared with placebo (103). In another randomized study of women with INOCA and CMD, quinapril treatment improved CFR in response to adenosine as well as angina pectoris symptoms after 16 weeks of treatment when compared with placebo (104).
Sacubitril-valsartan has been approved by the U.S. Food and Drug Administration for patients with symptomatic chronic HFrEF to reduce CVD mortality and hospitalization for HF compared with enalapril (105). Conversely, sacubitril-valsartan failed to meet a statistical difference on the primary composite endpoint (total HF hospitalizations and cardiovascular death) in the HFpEF population when compared with valsartan (106). The ongoing PRISTINE-HF (Study of Sacubitril/ValsarTan on MyocardIal OxygenatioN and Fibrosis in Heart Failure with

