Preserved Ejection Fraction; NCT04128891) will investigate the effects of this drug on microvascular function and ischemia, as assessed by oxygen sensitive-CMR at rest and after stress.
The effects of several other antianginal drugs, such as ivabradine, ranolazine, nicorandil, and trimetazidine, all cooperating in reducing oxygen demand, have been investigated in patients with CMD (101). Ranolazine has been extensively used in small-cohort randomized clinical trials, with contrasting efÔ¨Åcacy results in terms of CFR, symptom control, and stress test metrics (107,108). Ivabradine improved angina in patients with MVA without changing coronary microvascular function, suggesting that symptomatic improvement could be attributed to a heart rate‚Äì lowering effect. However, it has also been shown to improve CFR in patients with stable CAD even after heart rate correction, suggesting a potential role in microvascular function (101).
Nitrates have shown inconclusive effects in patients with CMD in multiple studies, probably burdened by bias in patient selection and inclusion criteria. However, short-acting nitrates can be useful to treat anginal attacks (especially in those patients with abnormal vasodilator reserve), but they are often only partially effective (101,107).
Phosphodiesterase type-5 inhibitors, such as sildenaÔ¨Ål, enhance the effect of NO by inhibiting the breakdown of cyclic guanosine monophosphate favoring smooth muscle relaxation. The positive effects of sildenaÔ¨Ål in CMD were Ô¨Årst investigated by Denardo et al (109) who demonstrated a signiÔ¨Åcant increase in CFR after the administration of the drug in patients with impaired microvascular function (109).

Fasudil, a speciÔ¨Åc Rho-kinase inhibitor, is highly effective in preventing ACh-induced coronary spasm and consequent myocardial ischemia in both patients with epicardial and microvascular spasm (110,111) (Table 4).
In patients with MVA, the Ô¨Åndings of elevated circulating concentrations of ET-1 led to conducting 2 small trials with ET-1 receptor antagonists (atrasentan and darusentan; NCT00271492; NCT00738049) with favorable proÔ¨Åles in patients with MVA. However, following neutral results from phase III trials relating to their primary indications, they were no longer investigated for application in MVA. A randomized controlled trial in patients with MVA with zibotentan (NCT04097314), a potent inhibitor of the ETA receptor with no ‚Äúoff-target‚Äù binding to the ETB receptor, is now ongoing (Table 4).
Recently, 2 classes of drugs, the sodium-glucose cotransporter 2 inhibitors (SGLT2i) and glucagonlike peptide 1-receptor antagonists, have consistently been demonstrated to reduce rates of major adverse CVD events in subjects with DM at high risk for CVD (112). SGLT2i and glucagon-like peptide 1-receptor antagonists could exert their effects by targeting several mediators of macrovascular and microvascular pathophysiology, such as cytokines and inÔ¨Çammation mediators, oxidative stressinduced endothelial dysfunction, and vascular smooth muscle cell proliferation, all etiological features of CMD (112). These data are further supported by the results recently published by Adingupu et al (113), who investigated the effects of SGLT2i on coronary microvascular function and cardiac contractility in a prediabetic mice model, showing

